lpture, architecture, and engraving bore witness to histories that frequently went untold; that they expressed key ideas standing behind events; and that they articulated concepts that would come to fruition only later.This groundbreaking reevaluation of Michelet's approach to history elucidates how writing about art provided a model for the historian's relation to, and interpretation of, the past, and thus for a new type of historiography-one that acknowledges and enacts the historian's own implication in the history he or she tells.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271085326zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271085326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271085326.jpg  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK